chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Even when we differ on the ideal system, most people agree that getting sick shouldn’t mean going without care or facing crushing debt. A workable middle ground is for government to guarantee that every resident has access to a defined package of essential, evidence-based services with strong protections against surprise bills and discrimination. Within that floor, public programs and private plans can compete and innovate under clear rules for price transparency, quality reporting, and fraud prevention. This approach protects universal access while using oversight and smart purchasing to keep costs sustainable.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Most of us can agree that no one should be denied essential care or face bankruptcy because they get sick, and that taxpayers deserve a system that is efficient and accountable. Government should guarantee a basic, nationwide floor of coverage for primary, preventive, emergency, and catastrophic care, while setting clear standards for quality, transparency, and fair pricing and cracking down on fraud and waste. Within that safety net, people should be able to choose among different plans and providers—including private options—so long as they meet the same rules and protect patients.
